on bay of the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident, in which she was driving a vehicle, going 80 kph when it hit a tree. She has a GCS of 8, HR 145/min, BP 85/40 mmHg and has agonal breathing. Bag-mask-valve ventilation is begun as the patient is prepared for intubation, whilst the rest of team addresses other issues.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best sedating agent for intubation in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Propofol","Thiopentone","Ketamine","Midazolam","Sevoflurane"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question requires knowledge of common anaesthetic agents and their adverse effects. The onset of action of all agents is relatively fast (arm-to-brain time) however most agents induce vasodilation and consequently hypotension. \u003Cstrong\u003EKetamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the only agent which increases blood pressure and heart rate. This is the ideal agent in this scenario where the low blood pressure is most likely secondary to hypovolaemic shock.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ketamine is the most appropriate sedating agent to use in the presence of hypovolaemic shock."],"references":["Ross W, Ellard L. Rapid Sequence Induction. World Federation of Societies of Anaesthethologists. 2016 May 24 [cited 2021 May 5]. Available from: https://anaesthesiology.gr/media/File/pdf/-Rapid-Sequence-Induction.pdf.","Nickson C. Rapid Sequence Intubation (RSI). Sydney (NSW): Life in the Fast Lane; 2020 Nov 3 [cited 2021 May 5]. Available from: https://litfl.com/rapid-sequence-intubation-rsi/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/14280"},"attributes":{"c